1

00:00:00,360  -->  00:00:05,275
So it might seem absurd to do this calculation of the standard deviation.

2

00:00:05,275  -->  00:00:08,420
I mean, it's such a complicated way to measure the spread

3

00:00:08,420  -->  00:00:11,985
of our data compared to the five number summary we saw earlier.

4

00:00:11,985  -->  00:00:16,250
But it turns out that the standard deviation is used all the

5

00:00:16,250  -->  00:00:21,140
time to get a single number to compare the spread of two data sets.

6

00:00:21,140  -->  00:00:25,340
It is kind of nice to be able to talk about how spread out our data are from one

7

00:00:25,340  -->  00:00:30,000
another without having to report an entire table of values.

8

00:00:30,000  -->  00:00:32,240
We can just compare the standard deviation for

9

00:00:32,240  -->  00:00:35,315
one group to the standard deviation of another group.

10

00:00:35,315  -->  00:00:39,150
And we have a way to tell which dataset is more spread out.

11

00:00:39,150  -->  00:00:42,380
Having one number simplifies the amount of

12

00:00:42,380  -->  00:00:46,230
information that the person you're reporting to needs to consume.

13

00:00:46,230  -->  00:00:48,545
Having the single value also has

14

00:00:48,545  -->  00:00:52,845
other advantages with regard to what is known as inferential statistics,

15

00:00:52,845  -->  00:00:55,055
but that's beyond what we need to know now.

16

00:00:55,055  -->  00:00:59,210
For now, we just need to know that we have a way to take all of

17

00:00:59,210  -->  00:01:01,580
our values and get a single number

18

00:01:01,580  -->  00:01:05,280
that tells us how spread out they are from one another.
